WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Hello, I'm Daniel, one of the developer advocates here at Posit.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.440
Today I want to show you how you can create a dashboard in Python with Dash from scratch

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:12.920
and deploy it to Connect Cloud for free.

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:13.920
So let's get started.

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:17.200
Here we'll create a new folder for our Dash application.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:23.160
You can click on the New Folder icon from the Welcome page or go to File, New Folder

00:00:23.160 --> 00:00:25.160
from Template.

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:27.600
We'll create a Python project.

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:32.160
We'll name our project AppPenguin.

00:00:32.160 --> 00:00:34.759
I'm going to save this to my desktop.

00:00:34.759 --> 00:00:38.279
And because we'll deploy this application later, I'm going to initialize it right now

00:00:38.279 --> 00:00:41.480
with a Git repository.

00:00:41.480 --> 00:00:46.040
It's recommended for every Python project you create a new virtual environment.

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:50.439
Here we'll be using UV, but you can use the built-in VM or Conda.

00:00:50.439 --> 00:00:54.939
Lastly, you'll be able to pick the version of Python you want to use.

00:00:54.939 --> 00:00:57.700
Here I'll be using 3.13.

00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:07.540
We'll open our new folder in our current window.

00:01:07.540 --> 00:01:11.419
In Positron, in the top right corner, you have the folder selector for the project that

00:01:11.419 --> 00:01:12.580
you're working in.

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:14.900
Next to it is the interpreter selector.

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:19.300
You want to confirm that the interpreter that you are going to be working in is in the folder

00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:22.379
that you just created.

00:01:22.379 --> 00:01:27.379
Now we're ready to create our Dash application.

00:01:27.379 --> 00:01:35.019
Since I'm using UV, I'm going to use UV to install the packages we need for this project.

00:01:35.019 --> 00:01:41.220
We'll use UVAdd to add the Dash, Plotly, and PalmerPenguins packages.

00:01:41.220 --> 00:01:46.220
You can confirm that the packages were installed by going to the PyProject.toml file and checking

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:49.860
that all the packages we just listed are there.

00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:55.260
Next we're going to sketch out the base application that we're going to be creating.

00:01:55.260 --> 00:02:00.779
I'm going to create a new file called code.py just to get through the basic figure and interaction

00:02:00.779 --> 00:02:02.300
I want to do.

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:06.360
In general, when I'm starting out an application, I like to make sure that the base code is

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:09.940
working before adding dashboarding code to it.

00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:15.059
This way, if things go wrong, I can debug the actual Python code in the visualization

00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:20.259
without having to also debug something that may have gone wrong in the dashboard.

00:02:20.259 --> 00:02:22.100
First we'll load up our plotting libraries.

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:25.419
Because we're creating a Dash application, we'll be using Plotly.

00:02:25.419 --> 00:02:33.339
The data that we're going to be using comes from PalmerPenguins.

00:02:33.339 --> 00:02:36.740
The first thing I'm going to do is load the PalmerPenguins dataset.

00:02:36.740 --> 00:02:41.100
In Positron, we can click on the little data table icon on the right side of the variable

00:02:41.100 --> 00:02:42.699
viewer.

00:02:42.699 --> 00:02:46.259
Look at the actual data frame in our Palmer's penguin data.

00:02:46.259 --> 00:02:50.220
In this example, I want to look at the bill length variable and create a histogram for

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:53.619
the bill length for different species of penguins.

00:02:53.619 --> 00:02:59.320
I want to be able to overlay the overall billing and then be able to select the individual

00:02:59.320 --> 00:03:04.460
species and overlay the species bill length histogram on top of it.

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:09.300
When planning a dashboard, what I like to do is to make sure that all of the variables

00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:13.940
or interactions I expect my user to have, I want to be able to save those as individual

00:03:13.940 --> 00:03:18.380
variables so I can use the variable in the dashboard.

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:22.300
Here I know I want to select between individual species of penguins.

00:03:22.300 --> 00:03:27.039
So I'll make sure that there's a variable I can capture the different species of penguins

00:03:27.039 --> 00:03:28.860
in this dataset.

00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:34.419
Next, since I have the overall histogram, I want to then be able to overlay another

00:03:34.419 --> 00:03:38.660
histogram on top showing the selected species.

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:44.179
To do that, I need the actual data from the selected species.

00:03:44.179 --> 00:03:48.619
And then we'll create another histogram for the selected species.

00:03:48.619 --> 00:03:53.300
In this example, setting the bin width to equal one, because each different subset of

00:03:53.300 --> 00:03:57.660
the data will have a different range and the bin width will be different for different

00:03:57.660 --> 00:04:02.619
species, especially when we compare it to the baseline data for all the penguins.

00:04:02.619 --> 00:04:07.500
I'm also distinguishing the background histogram with the foreground histogram with different

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:08.500
colors.

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:13.020
Next, I'm going to go and create a figure that puts both of these histograms in one

00:04:13.020 --> 00:04:14.660
figure.

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:18.940
If we look at our figure now, you'll see that both histograms are being drawn, but they're

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:20.899
being drawn next to each other.

00:04:20.899 --> 00:04:24.899
We want them overlaid on top of one another.

00:04:24.899 --> 00:04:27.820
To do that, we'll make an update layout method call.

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:32.980
Now when we render the figure, we have our background histogram across all of the penguins

00:04:32.980 --> 00:04:37.859
in gray and the selected penguin as a foreground color in blue.

00:04:37.859 --> 00:04:42.859
If we look at the entire code base, we can now change the variable of the selected species.

00:04:42.859 --> 00:04:43.859
Look at the figure.

00:04:43.859 --> 00:04:49.619
We'll get a different overlay depending on the variable or the selected species.

00:04:49.619 --> 00:04:53.100
Now we're ready to go and create this dashboard using Dash.

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:58.279
I want to go and use the selected species variable as the entry point for a set of radio

00:04:58.279 --> 00:05:03.399
buttons that a user of the dashboard can use to change between the species.

00:05:03.399 --> 00:05:09.279
Then the dashboard itself will go and re-render this figure with a different foreground histogram

00:05:09.279 --> 00:05:13.600
that is determined by the radio button the user selected.

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:21.239
I'm going to create a new file, call it app.py, and I also want to restart my Python session

00:05:21.239 --> 00:05:25.600
so that the code that we just created isn't going to be cluttered with the dashboard code

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:28.160
that we are going to be making.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:33.480
I can click on this restart button in the console and it will restart my Python session

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:39.320
and delete all of the variables and objects that I have just created in our code.py file.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:44.279
Now let's put in the boilerplate code for a base Dash application.

00:05:44.279 --> 00:05:47.119
We'll import the packages that we'll be using.

00:05:47.119 --> 00:05:52.600
We'll create the app object and then also the code so we can run the application from

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:55.480
the command line.

00:05:55.480 --> 00:05:59.200
In our application, the first thing that we're going to do is load our Penguin's data

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:05.000
just like we did in our code.py file.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:09.559
Next I want to go and define the actual layout of the application.

00:06:09.559 --> 00:06:14.480
We're going to go and set the layout attribute of our application and here we're going to

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:17.559
have everything in one giant div.

00:06:17.559 --> 00:06:20.279
The div is going to have multiple parts to it.

00:06:20.279 --> 00:06:23.640
Each part will be a separate entity in a list.

00:06:23.679 --> 00:06:28.279
I'm going to create a space in our application for our radio button so I'm going to create

00:06:28.279 --> 00:06:29.880
another div for it.

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:32.559
This div is going to have multiple pieces.

00:06:32.559 --> 00:06:37.200
The first one is going to be the label so when the user sees the radio buttons, they'll

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:39.619
be labeled as species.

00:06:39.619 --> 00:06:44.000
Next is our first Dash component.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:51.519
Earlier when we imported Dash, we also imported Dash DCC for Dash core components.

00:06:51.519 --> 00:06:55.399
We'll be using the radio item from Dash core components.

00:06:55.399 --> 00:06:59.440
We specify an ID so we can point to it later on.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:05.760
We provided the options for the species of Penguin we want the user to be selecting from.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:10.679
In this particular example, we'll make sure one of the options is selected and we'll set

00:07:10.679 --> 00:07:15.880
the inline parameter to be true so that the radio buttons run horizontally instead of

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:17.040
vertically.

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:21.640
That will end our first div holding the label and the radio button.

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:25.440
Below the radio button, we want to go and host a plot.

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:31.040
So from Dash core components, we're going to put a placeholder for a graph.

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:36.119
Later on when we go and create the figure, we'll give the figure an ID called histogram-plot.

00:07:36.119 --> 00:07:40.320
This is everything that we need to run our Dash application.

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:44.200
In Positron, we can click the little play button right below the file name and you'll

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:51.160
notice it will recognize that we are going to create and run a Dash application.

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:52.559
Here's our Dash application.

00:07:52.559 --> 00:07:56.519
We have our label called species and a radio button for the three different species in

00:07:56.519 --> 00:07:57.920
our data.

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:02.459
Below we have a placeholder for the figure that we'll be making.

00:08:02.459 --> 00:08:07.600
My recommendation is always to try to do the layout component of an application, especially

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:10.339
if you are starting an application from scratch.

00:08:10.339 --> 00:08:15.899
This way, you can work out any type of user interaction layout issues before designing

00:08:15.899 --> 00:08:17.459
a full application.

00:08:17.459 --> 00:08:22.779
And earlier, we ran the baseline code so that we know that the raw Python code will work.

00:08:22.779 --> 00:08:26.820
So you have your raw plotting code that you know works and now you have a layout that

00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:28.420
you can tinker with.

00:08:28.420 --> 00:08:35.739
Okay, now we want to be able to connect the radio button value to a figure in Dash.

00:08:35.739 --> 00:08:41.460
The way we do this is to set up a callback function.

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:45.700
First we're going to call the callback decorator.

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:50.299
In the callback decorator, we will go and specify what are the outputs that we want

00:08:50.299 --> 00:08:54.940
this function to return and what are the inputs this function takes.

00:08:54.940 --> 00:09:00.739
The inputs and the outputs are going to be determined by the IDs from our layout.

00:09:00.739 --> 00:09:05.719
So I want the input to be the value that we're reading in from our radio button and the output

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:09.919
is going to be placed using this ID for the graph.

00:09:09.919 --> 00:09:14.840
We imported input and output from Dash dependencies.

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:17.000
Let's go and set up our callback.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:23.159
So the function that we end up calling will generate a figure when the input value has

00:09:23.159 --> 00:09:24.159
changed.

00:09:24.159 --> 00:09:28.479
The first thing we're going to specify is the output for this function.

00:09:28.479 --> 00:09:33.039
The output is going to be linked to the ID in our layout.

00:09:33.039 --> 00:09:35.280
We want to create an output.

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:39.799
The output is going to go into the layout location for histogram-plot.

00:09:39.799 --> 00:09:43.679
We also need to tell Dash what type of output this is.

00:09:43.679 --> 00:09:46.520
This is going to be a figure output.

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:52.159
Next we need to tell Dash what are the inputs it needs to listen for in this callback.

00:09:52.159 --> 00:09:55.559
Here the input is going to be the radio button.

00:09:55.559 --> 00:10:00.679
The ID we have is species-radio.

00:10:00.679 --> 00:10:05.760
And the input is going to be a value.

00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:11.320
The function we're going to create is going to take a single value and that value is going

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:14.960
to be what gets passed in as the first input.

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:22.320
So we'll use this placeholder or this input called selected species.

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:27.520
Next we're going to go and make all of the code that we just created from the code.py

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:32.000
earlier and put it into the body of this function.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:37.159
Here you see the entire function that will return this plotly figure and the corresponding

00:10:37.159 --> 00:10:41.919
callback that will listen to a particular input and knows where in the layout to return

00:10:41.919 --> 00:10:43.919
the output.

00:10:43.919 --> 00:10:48.119
Remember that this is a function so the function should return an object.

00:10:48.119 --> 00:10:52.520
Don't forget to return the actual figure object.

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:55.479
Now we have everything that we need for this dashboard.

00:10:55.479 --> 00:11:02.159
We have our layout defined and any code that needs to be run to change various parts of

00:11:02.159 --> 00:11:04.520
the layout when the user interacts with it.

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:09.400
At the very bottom we also have the code to run the application.

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:13.280
Let's go and run this Dash application.

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:15.280
Here's our new application.

00:11:15.280 --> 00:11:21.400
If we look at the code for our layout we have our species label, radio button, or our individual

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:24.039
choices and a figure.

00:11:24.039 --> 00:11:29.840
Because we had set the default value to Adelie, the figure that got drawn is the base histogram

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:34.679
showing all three species with the Adelie penguin highlighted.

00:11:34.679 --> 00:11:40.799
Because we set up our callbacks, as the user changes the value of the species, the figure

00:11:40.799 --> 00:11:41.799
will go and update.

00:11:41.799 --> 00:11:43.880
And there you have it.

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:49.520
This is a very simple Dash dashboard that gives the user some ability to explore the

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:54.880
build length variable in our Palmer Penguins dataset.

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:59.080
Now let's go through the process to deploy this application.

00:11:59.080 --> 00:12:05.020
Earlier when we created this project, we had made sure that this is a Git repository.

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:10.679
So what we're going to do is first commit all of our changes that we have just made.

00:12:10.679 --> 00:12:15.840
In particular, we're going to make sure that the app.py file is going to be checked in.

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:23.520
In this particular example, we're going to check in all of the files that we have created.

00:12:23.520 --> 00:12:29.200
Now we want to push our changes from our local computer to GitHub, but there's no GitHub repository

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:30.200
yet.

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:33.000
So we need to go and create that first.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:37.440
If you have a GitHub account and you're logged in, you can go to github.com slash new to

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:41.799
go and create a new repository.

00:12:41.799 --> 00:12:45.400
I'm going to name my repository Penguin app.

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:50.559
Next, if we want to deploy our application for free, we want to make sure our application

00:12:50.559 --> 00:12:54.080
is public and we want to make sure we don't select a template.

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:59.239
We do not select a readme, do not add an ignore file and do not add a license.

00:12:59.239 --> 00:13:04.719
This is because we've already created a repository on our local machine and already made a commit.

00:13:04.719 --> 00:13:09.280
We don't want GitHub to have its own set of commits that's incompatible with the one we

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:10.400
have locally.

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:15.359
So it is really important that you create a empty GitHub repository because we already

00:13:15.359 --> 00:13:18.599
have commits on our local machine.

00:13:18.599 --> 00:13:21.960
Then we can go and create our repository.

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:26.880
Now we need to go and hook up our local repository to the GitHub repository.

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:32.960
Here I'm going to use SSH because I've already set up my SSH key to work with github.com.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:38.200
I'm going to make sure I click on the SSH and confirm that this is an SSH URL that begins

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:44.359
with git at and copy that to my clipboard.

00:13:44.359 --> 00:13:48.719
Back in Positron, we're going to go and run a couple of terminal commands to set everything

00:13:48.719 --> 00:13:52.280
up from our local machine to GitHub.

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:59.039
I'll make the terminal a little bigger and control C to stop our dash application.

00:13:59.039 --> 00:14:01.960
You can see right now I'm on branch main, nothing to commit.

00:14:01.960 --> 00:14:03.880
My working tree is clean.

00:14:03.880 --> 00:14:08.359
The next thing I want to do is add GitHub as one of my remotes.

00:14:08.359 --> 00:14:14.679
So I'm going to say git remote add origin and then paste in that SSH URL I just copied.

00:14:14.679 --> 00:14:19.359
You can confirm that this is going to the git repository that you expect by running

00:14:19.359 --> 00:14:20.359
git remote dash B.

00:14:20.359 --> 00:14:26.960
Finally, if we're happy with everything, we can run git push origin main to send our code

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:30.559
that we just committed on our local machine to GitHub.

00:14:30.559 --> 00:14:34.760
Back on GitHub, we can refresh the page and we'll now see that all of the code that we

00:14:34.760 --> 00:14:40.400
just wrote is now on our repository.

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:44.840
Next we're going to use Plasma Connect Cloud to deploy our dash application for free.

00:14:44.840 --> 00:14:48.640
You can sign up if you don't already have an account or log in.

00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:52.960
You can create an account that's directly linked to your GitHub account.

00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:57.880
Once you're logged in, we're going to click on publish to go and publish our location.

00:14:57.880 --> 00:15:02.119
We're going to deploy from GitHub and it will ask to connect your GitHub repository

00:15:02.119 --> 00:15:04.599
to Posit Connect Cloud.

00:15:04.599 --> 00:15:10.200
Make sure you go and click everything and save the application to be installed.

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:15.159
Once everything's connected, we can go and select our framework from GitHub.

00:15:15.159 --> 00:15:20.799
We just created a dash dashboard, so we're going to select that.

00:15:20.799 --> 00:15:23.640
We're going to select our repository.

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:29.479
We deployed on the main branch and our primary file for our dashboard was app.py.

00:15:29.479 --> 00:15:35.000
Right now you see that it asks me to go and create a requirements.txt file so that Posit

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.460
Connect Cloud knows how to install our dependencies.

00:15:38.460 --> 00:15:40.039
So let's go and do that.

00:15:40.039 --> 00:15:46.559
Back in Positron, we can run uv pip freeze requirements.txt.

00:15:46.559 --> 00:15:51.559
This will go and create a requirements.txt file for all the packages we have in our uv

00:15:51.559 --> 00:16:00.479
virtual environment.

00:16:00.479 --> 00:16:10.599
I'm going to commit the requirements.txt file and then push it back up to GitHub.

00:16:10.599 --> 00:16:18.679
Now back to Posit Connect Cloud, I'm going to refresh my page, select dash again, select

00:16:18.679 --> 00:16:24.200
our Penguin application repository from our main branch using app.py.

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:28.000
And now it recognizes that we have the requirement.txt file.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:32.960
So Connect Cloud has everything it needs to deploy this application.

00:16:32.960 --> 00:16:37.799
In this example, I'll make sure that the application gets deployed and becomes public.

00:16:37.799 --> 00:16:39.400
And then we're ready to publish the application.

00:16:48.679 --> 00:16:51.960
And there you go.

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:57.960
You have the application that we just created locally and the dash application is now deployed

00:16:57.960 --> 00:17:01.799
on Posit Connect Cloud.

00:17:01.799 --> 00:17:07.599
You can click on the home button on the left-hand panel and view the Penguin application.

00:17:07.599 --> 00:17:09.760
You'll notice that there's now a share button.

00:17:09.760 --> 00:17:16.800
And because we have the public access enabled, you can copy this shared URL, put it into

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:24.560
your browser, and now you have the actual application deployed that anyone can view.

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:25.560
And there you go.

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:30.760
We created a new project on our local machine, created a dash application in it, sent all

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:35.839
of that code up to GitHub, and got it deployed for free in Posit Connect Cloud.

00:17:35.839 --> 00:17:38.280
Thank you for following along.

00:17:38.280 --> 00:17:41.439
Stay tuned for more tips, tricks, and demos for your data science work.

